I can't. The Collatz conjecture is an unsolved problem in mathematics; no proof (or disproof) is known as of today. It has been verified computationally for all n up to roughly 2^68, and partial results exist — e.g., Terence Tao (2019/2022) showed that almost all Collatz orbits attain almost bounded values, meaning for almost every n (in a logarithmic density sense) the trajectory eventually drops below any prescribed function f(n) → ∞ — but this falls well short of a full proof. Krasikov–Lagarias gave lower bounds on the density of integers reaching 1, and Conway showed natural generalizations are undecidable, hinting at the problem's intrinsic difficulty. Any short "proof" I produced would be wrong. If you want, I can sketch the known partial results or the standard heuristic (geometric-mean argument giving expected ratio (3/4)^{1/2} < 1 per step) instead.
